body:
More:
I test fp16 and int8 model in cpu (Intel(R) Xeon(R) CPU E5-2650 v4)
f16 model converted using https://github.com/onnx/onnx-docker/blob/master/onnx-ecosystem/converter_scripts/float32_float16_onnx.ipynb
int8 model converted using https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/tree/master/onnxruntime/python/tools/quantization

* fp32: time 1s; cpu usage 600%
* fp16: time 1s; cpu usage 600%
* int8: time 4s; cpu usage 100%

It seems that fp16 and int8 model has no improvement in cpu.

The int8 GEMM in the last release was still single-threaded. A multi-threaded int8 GEMM was just turned on in master with PR#2844.

For the CPU, FP16 currently is handled by casting all operations to FP32. The GPU path does support FP16 natively.

issue.title: Which framework can export quantization model to onnx?

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body: I use post-training or training-aware quantization methods in pytorch, but those models cannot be exported to onnx format. Any frameworks support that? I want to make inference using onnxruntime.

body:
@tracysh 
I use the latest onnxruntime in master branch, but I also got similar result.

* fp32 model: time 40ms; cpu usage 450%
* int8 model: time 65ms; cpu usage  300%

Also cannot get performance improvement

I use resnet50 model in https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/tree/master/onnxruntime/python/tools/quantization/E2E_example_model

test code
```
import numpy as np
import onnxruntime as rt
import time

so = rt.SessionOptions()
so.intra_op_num_threads = 4
so.execution_mode = rt.ExecutionMode.ORT_SEQUENTIAL
so.graph_optimization_level = rt.GraphOptimizationLevel.ORT_DISABLE_ALL
sess = rt.InferenceSession('resnet50_int8.onnx', providers=['CPUExecutionProvider'], sess_options=so)

input_name = sess.get_inputs()[0].name
image = np.random.rand(1, 224, 224, 3).astype('float32')

for i in range(1000):
    t1 = time.time()
    output = sess.run(None, {input_name: image})
    t2 = time.time()
    print('time', t2 - t1)
```

quantization code
```
import onnx
from quantize import quantize, QuantizationMode

# Load the onnx model
model = onnx.load('resnet50_v1.onnx')
# Quantize
quantized_model = quantize(model, quantization_mode=QuantizationMode.IntegerOps, static=False)
# Save the quantized model
onnx.save(quantized_model, 'resnet50_int8.onnx')
```
Any idea?
